{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:18:06.513615+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 6e90e2d5b8c4ddca40dea68ada13a608abb2f4f7)", "id": "lc_35c3a875-8052-453d-9121-5999aad8ad97"}, {"type": "text", "text": "import logging\n\nimport sqlalchemy\nfrom databases import Database\nfrom sqlalchemy.orm import sessionmaker\nfrom sqlalchemy_utils import database_exists, create_database\n\nfrom .settings import settings\n\n\ndb = Database(settings.DB_URL)\nmetadata = sqlalchemy.MetaData()\nengine = sqlalchemy.create_engine(settings.DB_URL, pool_size=3, max_overflow=0)\nif not database_exists(engine.url):\n    create_database(engine.url)\n\nLocalSession = sessionmaker(autocommit=False, autoflush=False, bind=engine)\n\nmetadata.create_all(engine)\n\n\ndef get_db():\n    \"\"\"\n    A dependency for working with PostgreSQL\n    \"\"\"\n    try:\n        db = LocalSession()\n        yield db\n    except Exception as e:\n        logging.error(e)\n    finally:\n        db.close()\n", "id": "lc_47908eb1-f5dd-4a78-83cf-08a541edd455"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "aeb10307-1eaf-4a27-89f6-9110d18a0df4", "tool_call_id": "call_a7148c0ea996413e975c0e11", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:18:06.523460+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: e0f90ac88e1236616df18600c7f7a5f80ac113c6)", "id": "lc_860acd58-b346-4526-b438-1329d4a3436c"}, {"type": "text", "text": "from datetime import datetime, timedelta\nfrom typing import Any, Dict\n\nfrom fastapi.security import OAuth2PasswordBearer\nfrom jose import jwt\n\nfrom app.services import BaseService\nfrom app.settings import settings\n\n# for authentication that works seamlessly with OpenAPI\nreuseable_oauth = OAuth2PasswordBearer(\n    tokenUrl=\"/api/v1/user/login\",\n    scheme_name=\"JWT\"\n)\n\n\ndef hash_password(password: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Creates a hash of the password\"\"\"\n    hashed_password = settings.PASSWORD_HASHER.hash(password)\n    return hashed_password\n\n\ndef verify_password(plain_password: str, hashed_password: str) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Checks if a password corresponds to a hash\"\"\"\n    password_is_verified = settings.PASSWORD_HASHER.verify(\n        plain_password, hashed_password\n    )\n\n    return bool(password_is_verified)\n\n\ndef create_auth_token(payload: Dict[str, Any], expiry: int) -> str:\n    \"\"\"\n    This handles the encoding of user information into a token\n    that can be used. It is generic so as to accomodate access and\n    refresh token.\n    \"\"\"\n    expiry_delta = datetime.now() + timedelta(seconds=expiry)\n    data_to_encode = {\"expiry\": str(expiry_delta), \"data\": payload}\n    encoded_data: str = jwt.encode(\n        data_to_encode, settings.SECRET_KEY, settings.JWT_ALGORITHM\n    )\n\n    return encoded_data\n\n\nclass UserService(BaseService):\n    \"\"\"\n    This class helps perform bulk of activities required by the corresponding API\n    \"\"\"\n    def a_method(self):\n        \"\"\"\n        Here, the use of `self.save` is demonstrated.\n        Ensure to take out this method.\n        \"\"\"\n        model_instance = ...\n        self.save(model_instance)", "id": "lc_b39636ad-0acb-4e33-bc7d-2bc38704a9d6"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "5bd99d2f-3911-4b26-ad75-60ff64850d28", "tool_call_id": "call_eb5e6d377213426ca142a39b", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:18:27.317248+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have all the information needed. Here's the full explanation:\n\n---\n\n## How Application Settings Are Derived from Environment Variables\n\nThis template uses a centralized **`Settings` class** in `app/settings.py` that reads all configuration from environment variables via Python's `os.environ.get()`. The environment variables themselves are loaded from a `.env` file, as configured in `docker-compose.yml` (`env_file: ./.env`). A `.example.env` is provided as a template.\n\n### Database URLs\n\nThe database configuration is built from **five separate PostgreSQL environment variables** that are composed into connection URLs:\n\n| Environment Variable     | Setting Attribute | Purpose                   |\n|--------------------------|-------------------|---------------------------|\n| `POSTGRES_USER`          | `DB_USER`         | Database username         |\n| `POSTGRES_PASSWORD`      | `DB_PASSWORD`     | Database password         |\n| `POSTGRES_DB`            | `DB_DB`           | Primary database name     |\n| `POSTGRES_PORT`          | `DB_PORT`         | Database port             |\n| `POSTGRES_HOST`          | `DB_HOST`         | Database hostname         |\n| `POSTGRES_TEST_DB`       | `TEST_DB`         | Test database name        |\n\nThese are assembled into two SQLAlchemy connection URLs:\n\n- **`DB_URL`** (primary): `postgresql+psycopg2://{DB_USER}:{DB_PASSWORD}@{DB_HOST}:{DB_PORT}/{DB_DB}`\n- **`TEST_DB_URL`** (testing): `postgresql+psycopg2://{DB_USER}:{DB_PASSWORD}@{DB_HOST}:{DB_PORT}/{TEST_DB}`\n\nBoth URLs share the same credentials, host, and port — they only differ in the database name. With the example `.env` values, `DB_URL` resolves to `postgresql+psycopg2://sasori:sasori@postgres:5432/akatsuki`.\n\nThese URLs are consumed in `app/db.py`, which creates both an async `Database` instance and a synchronous SQLAlchemy `engine` (with `pool_size=3`, `max_overflow=0`). On startup, it checks whether the database exists and creates it if needed via `sqlalchemy_utils`.\n\n### Token Settings\n\nToken/JWT settings are a mix of **environment variables** and **hardcoded values**:\n\n| Attribute                      | Source                              | Example Value              |\n|--------------------------------|-------------------------------------|----------------------------|\n| `SECRET_KEY`                   | `SECRET_KEY` env var                | `meandyouaretogether`      |\n| `JWT_ALGORITHM`                | Hardcoded                           | `\"HS256\"`                  |\n| `ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRY_TIME`     | Hardcoded (not configurable via env)| `60 * 30` = 1800 seconds (30 min) |\n| `REFRESH_TOKEN_EXPIRY_TIME`    | Hardcoded                           | `60 * 24 * 365` = 525,600 seconds (~1 year) |\n| `PASSWORD_HASHER`              | Hardcoded                           | `CryptContext(schemes=[\"bcrypt\"], deprecated=\"auto\")` |\n\nThe `SECRET_KEY` is the critical env-derived setting — it's used by `auth/services.py` to sign JWT tokens via `python-jose`. The `create_auth_token()` function encodes a payload with an expiry timestamp, signs it with `SECRET_KEY` using the `HS256` algorithm, and returns the resulting token string.\n\n### Redis Configuration\n\nRedis has **two optional environment variables** with built-in fallback defaults:\n\n| Environment Variable | Setting Attribute | Default Value |\n|----------------------|-------------------|---------------|\n| `REDIS_HOST`         | `REDIS_HOST`      | `\"localhost\"` |\n| `REDIS_PORT`         | `REDIS_PORT`      | `\"6379\"`      |\n\nThese use `environ.get(key, default)`, so they gracefully fall back to standard Redis defaults if the env vars aren't set. In the docker-compose setup, the `.example.env` overrides them to `redis` (the service name) and `6379` respectively, matching the internal Docker network.\n\n### Other Environment-Derived Settings\n\nA few more settings round out the configuration:\n\n| Env Variable    | Attribute        | Type Coercion       | Purpose                        |\n|-----------------|------------------|---------------------|--------------------------------|\n| `ALLOWED_HOST`  | `ALLOWED_HOST`   | String (no default) | Host binding                   |\n| `DEBUG`         | `DEBUG`          | `bool()`            | Debug mode flag                |\n| `PORT`          | `ALLOWED_PORT`   | `int()`             | Application port (default 11000 in `.env`) |\n\n**Note on `DEBUG`:** This uses `bool(environ.get(\"DEBUG\"))`, which means *any* string value (including `\"False\"`) will evaluate to `True` since `bool(\"False\")` is `True` in Python. Only if `DEBUG` is completely unset (returning `None`) would it be `False`.\n\n### How It All Flows Together\n\n```\n.env file\n  ↓ (loaded by docker-compose env_file)\nos.environ\n  ↓ (read by os.environ.get())\napp/settings.py::Settings class (singleton: `settings`)\n  ↓ (imported where needed)\napp/db.py        → uses DB_URL, TEST_DB_URL\nauth/services.py → uses SECRET_KEY, JWT_ALGORITHM, PASSWORD_HASHER\n```", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 1156, "prompt_tokens": 10693, "total_tokens": 11849, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 16, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 9920, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.001377687, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.000371967, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.00100572}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780863486-SWPdg8l4GYxOqqf0i81a", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, 